In python you may encounter two different types of errors, syntax errors and exceptions. When you don’t follow python’s syntax and or you forget to add an indention, you get an error. Unlike syntax errors, exceptions are raised during the execution of the program interpreting the normal flow of the application. 

The try statement checks for any exceptions in the code you have entered. If you have any exception errors in your code, then the exception statement is used to print out what needs to be shown, when an exception occurs.

For example:

For  i  in range(5):
	Try:
		print( i / 0)
	Except ZeroDivision Error as e:
		print( e, “ → Division by 0 is not allowed, sorry!” )

As you can see here in this example, dividing any integer by zero will give you an error because zero cannot be divided by a number. So, since this example produces an exception, you wanted to alert python with your  try statement that every time zero is divided, print the except statement below it. In other words, instead of python producing an error message when you have an exception, you are able as a coder to tell python what you want printed if there is an error in your code, that is the power of the except statement. In the above code, “ → Division by 0 is not allowed, sorry!” would be printed because of the except statement instead of the error syntax message.

If the code inside your indented try statement does not generate any type of errors, then python will move past the except statement as if it was not there.

You can also add multiple except statements under your try statement to be extra cautious and cover any type of errors that may appear in your code. A common question when using the except statement is:

What if I want to catch all possible exceptions that can be generated by the code located under the try statement?
Well, you can just use the except statement alone, without specifying an exception name to be expected.

Example:

Try:
	Print( i / 0)
Except:
	Print( error)

This method is however not recommended because it just shows an error message and does nor establish the root cause of the error. It is better and way more efficient to label each exception statement by type of error as such:

Try:
	Print( i /0 )
Except ZeroDivisionError:
	Print ( “Division by 0 is just wrong!” )
Except Name Error:
	Print ( “Name Error detected!” )
Except Value Error:
	Print ( “Wrong Value!” )

All of these exception statements for errors in your code can possibly be produced.

When using the else statement in a line of code that includes a try and except statement, if there is no error in your try statement, the else statement will print and bypass the except statement.

When the ‘finally statement’ is used, the line of code gets printed out, whether or not there is an error. 

Example:

Try:
	Print: ( 4/ 0 )
Except ZeroDivisionError:
	Print: ( “ Not allowed” )
Finally:
	Print: ( “This line of code will be printed no matter!” )

As you can see the line of code underneath the ‘finally statement’ will always be printed no matter what happens, if there is an error or not!

