Lecture #116 talks about opening and reading Python files.

/n = new line of code.
/t = this will tab within each line of your code. In other words, indent the line.
/u

Bare in mind, when adding using the open function and adding a path to your text file, if there is any /n, /t, /u, this will cause exceptions to be raised in your code. To avoid this, you need to add double back slashes as such.

Ex: D:\\Users\\Coding\\Trouble\\Routers.text

Another way to avoid this issue is to use an alternative line of code:

Ex: F = open(r “C:\coding\try.py”, “r”) → the “r” in front of the path for file tells python everything in the file is real and it avoids any exceptions.

Quick Tips for opening, closing, writing, and reading files in Python:

f = open(r “C:\coding\try.py”, “r”)

f.seek(0) → This function should always be used before using the read function. The reason being is because it allows the developer to read the text in the python file from the beginning, instead of the end. Without using this function first, the read function will show a empty set.

f.read() → This function shows what is present in the Python file.

f.write() → This function allows you to write text in a Python file. But you need to open the Python file with the “w” disposition first. 

f.close() → After you are typing writing in a Python file, it is imperative to close the file right after. If you do not so by using this function, the changes will not be saved.

f.readlines()[1] → Readlines has the capability of going into your python file and choosing which line of code you want to be recited back to you. So in this example, the first line of one’s program will be produced in the output. 

*f = open(r “C:\coding\try.py”, “a”) → The “a” or append function allows you to add more text or data in a file without erasing the existing data that is already placed into the file.

By the way, there is a method for closing files automatically after opening them up. It is the with … as function.
